MercadoLibre $MELI: Latin America’s E-Commerce & Fintech Powerhouse Trading at 2019 Valuations

$MELI continues to dominate Latin America with a flywheel between commerce and fintech few can match. Revenue grew +33.8% YoY (+53% FX-neutral) in Q2, while operating income hit a record $825M. Despite the growth, the stock is up only +10% in six months, leaving its Forward EV/Sales at 3.6, near historic lows.

Margins remain resilient. Free cash flow margin expanded to 38.7%, even as sales & marketing spend surged. Fintech revenue +40.3% YoY outpaced total growth, driven by Mercado Pago’s 68M active users and robust TPV growth of +39.4%. Commerce held strong at +29.3% YoY, with GMV up +20.6% and the take rate rising to 25.2%, showing stronger monetization per transaction.

Argentina’s turnaround is striking—+77% YoY revenue growth, now 22% of total, as management’s strategic focus pays off. Mexico continues to scale efficiently through fulfillment and cross-border synergies. Brazil’s low-ticket strategy is gaining traction, with free shipping down to R$19, unlocking new buyers and engagement.

Credit quality is improving. NPLs over 90 days stabilized at 18.5%, far below 2022 highs. Over 1.5M new credit cards were issued, and Brazil’s card business is now NIM-positive. Assets under management more than doubled YoY, reflecting strong ecosystem engagement.

Yet one question lingers—can margins hold as competition in low-ASP categories intensifies and MercadoLibre invests more heavily in logistics and marketing to defend share?

Still, the long-term story is intact. $MELI operates in a $1T TAM across e-commerce and fintech, with Latin America’s online penetration at only 11%. Management plans $9.2B in investments across Brazil and Mexico, reinforcing logistics dominance and accelerating growth.

The moat is massive: economies of scale, 218M users, proprietary logistics, AI-driven personalization, and a top-50 global brand valued at $49.8B. Despite near-term margin pressure, growth fundamentals remain exceptional.

At a Forward P/E of 40 and a PEG ratio near 1.0, $MELI looks undervalued for a business compounding earnings at a ~47% rate.

In October, I increased my position — $MELI now makes up 8.6% of my portfolio.
Still dominant. Still growing. Still overlooked.

$MELI Mercado Libre: Still the E-Commerce Powerhouse of Latin America

Margins and growth momentum remain strong. In Brazil, the company leads with a commanding 35% share—more than double Amazon’s—and pulls over 237 million monthly visits and 17 million app users. Scale and engagement still anchor the story.

In Mexico, the next growth frontier, Mercado Libre controls 30% of the market, trailing Amazon’s 40%. Yet it’s deploying $3.4B in 2025 to expand logistics and hire 10,000 people. That level of investment signals long-term intent, not retreat.

Can it defend dominance across every market as competition intensifies? Shopee’s surge in visits in Brazil and Amazon’s stronghold in Mexico suggest the battle is far from over.

Argentina remains its fortress with 35% share, far ahead of Amazon at 20%. But in Chile and Colombia, where local players like Falabella and Alkosto dominate, Mercado Libre lags with just 5% share—though both markets are growing fast, offering a new runway for expansion.

The big picture: Mercado Libre is scaling deeper into logistics and market reach. Its leadership in Brazil and Argentina provides cash flow to fund a strategic push into faster-growing but underpenetrated markets. Dominance today, but the next phase will test how far that lead can stretch.
